      "is not a forest, because it can have a triangle.\n\nBut perhaps the size Ramsey of `G = K_3` is linear in the number of edges of `H`? I'm not sure.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps the condition on `G` is impossible unless `G` is very small. \n\nLet's take `k = 2`. The condition is that every subset of size `2` has at most `1` edge, which means no multiple edges, which is true for simple graphs. \n\nWait no, for `k = 2`, any subset of size `2` is an edge, so it must have `≤ 1` edge, which means no multiple edges, but in Lean, `G` is a simple graph, so this is automatically satisfied. \n\nSimilarly, for `k = 3`, any subset of size `3` must have `≤ 3` edges, which is fine unless you have `K_4`. \n\nBut for `k = 4`, any subset of `4` vertices must have `≤ 5` edges. \n\nBut if `G` is `K_4`, then taking `S = G` gives `6 ≤ 5`, which is false. So `G` cannot be `K_4`.\n\nSimilarly, if `G` is a complete graph on `n` vertices, then for `S = G`, the number of edges is `n(n-1)/2`, while `2n - 3`, and `n(n-1)/2 ≤ 2n - 3` only if `n(n-1) ≤ 4n - 6`, i.e., `n² - 5n + 6 ≤ 0`, `(n - 2)(n - 3) ≤ 0`, which is `n ∈ [2, 3]`.\n\nThus, only `K_2`, `K_3` satisfy this as complete graphs. \n\nBut non-complete graphs can as well. For example, a triangle plus an isolated vertex. \n\nBut for `G = K_3 + K_1`, the subsets of size `2` are fine (`1 ≤ 1`). Subsets of size `3`: if they include the isolated vertex, they have at most `2` edges (`2 ≤ 3`). \n\nBut perhaps the statement of the problem is not the correct formalization of Erdős's problem, because the original asks if `r̂(G, H) ≪ m`, but in Lean it asks for `c > 0`, and perhaps this `c` cannot be uniform or something.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps the condition is intended to be that for every subset of `k` vertices, the number of edges is `≤ k - 1`, which would imply the graph is a forest. But Lean says `2k - 3`. \n\nAlternatively, perhaps the theorem is false as stated because one can find a graph `G` that satisfies the condition but `r̂(G, H)` is not bounded by `c · m` for any `c`. \n\nBut I'm not sure yet. Let me try to think of a concrete `G`.\n\nTake `G = K_3`. \n\nIt satisfies the condition: \n- subsets of size `2` have `1 ≤ 1`.\n- subsets of size `3` have `3 ≤ 3`.\n- subsets of size `k ≥ 4` are not present because `G` has only `3` vertices.\n\nNow for `H` being `K_n`, `r̂(K_3, K_n)` is `n^2 - n + 1` (roughly), and `m = n(n-1)/2`. \n\nWe would have `n² - n + 1 ≤ c * n(n-1)/2`. For large `n`, this is `n² ≤ c n² / 2`, so `c ≥ 2`. \n\nBut it seems to hold for `c = 4`, because `n² - n + 1 ≤ 4 * n(n-1)/2 = 2n² - 2n`, i.e., `n² - n + 1 ≤ 2n² - 2n`, i.e., `0 ≤ n² - n - 1`, which is true for `n ≥ 2`.\n\nSo, perhaps for `G = K_3`, there is indeed a `c`.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps for every `G` satisfying the sparsity condition, there exists `c` such that for any `H`, the size Ramsey is bounded by `c * |E(H)|`.\n\nBut I",
